{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525915"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:18:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:18:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14101"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14101","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14101"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.59,0.05,0.1,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6771"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55875"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6771"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14101"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41423"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1086"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1845"},{"type":"tags","id":"2134"},{"type":"tags","id":"2956"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14863"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43483"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55875"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of swollen legs and face. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus diagnosed 10 years ago and hypertension. Her regular medications include metformin, gliclazide, and ramipril. On examination, she appears unwell with generalised oedema. Her pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 150/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum albumin: 24 g/L (35-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum creatinine: 120 \u00b5mol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EeGFR: 48 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E24-hour urine protein: 5.5 g (\u0026lt;0.15)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinalysis: 3+ protein.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine microscopy: Normal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the LEAST likely cause of this patient\u0027s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amyloidosis","ANCA-associated vasculitis","Membranous nephropathy","Diabetic nephropathy","Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features of nephrotic syndrome, including generalised oedema, hypoalbuminaemia, and significant proteinuria. Given her history of long-standing diabetes, the most likely cause is diabetic nephropathy. However, the question asks for the least likely cause among the options provided.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EANCA-associated vasculitis\u003C/strong\u003E is the least likely cause of this patient\u0027s presentation. ANCA-associated vasculitis typically presents with rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis, characterized by acute kidney injury, haematuria, and often systemic symptoms such as fever, weight loss, and multi-organ involvement. It rarely presents with pure nephrotic syndrome as seen in this case, and often presents with microscopic haematuria (unlike the normal urine microscopy in this case).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common secondary cause of nephrotic syndrome in adults, especially in those with a long-standing history of diabetes. It typically presents with gradually increasing proteinuria and declining renal function, which fits this patient\u0027s presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFocal segmental glomerulosclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E (FSGS) is an important cause of nephrotic syndrome in both children and adults. It can be primary or secondary to various conditions, including obesity and hypertension, both of which may be relevant in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMembranous nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E is another common cause of nephrotic syndrome in adults. It can be primary or secondary to various conditions, including autoimmune diseases, infections, and malignancies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmyloidosis\u003C/strong\u003E, while less common, is a secondary cause of nephrotic syndrome, especially in older adults. It can be associated with chronic inflammatory conditions or plasma cell dyscrasias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, while diabetic nephropathy is the most likely diagnosis, a renal biopsy would be necessary to confirm the underlying cause of nephrotic syndrome, especially given the degree of renal impairment. The normal urine microscopy makes some glomerulonephritides less likely but does not rule them out entirely. Management would include optimising blood pressure control, optimising glycemic control, and consideration of medications such as ACE inhibitors or ARBs to reduce proteinuria. Further investigations for secondary causes and immunosuppressive therapies may be required depending on the findings of renal biopsy. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nephrotic syndrome is the constellation of heavy proteinuria, oedema, hypoalbuminaemia and/or hyperchlosterolaemia.","Conditions which typically present with nephrotic syndrome include minimal change disease, focal segmental glomerulosclerosis, membranous nephropathy, diabetic nephropathy and amyloidosis."],"references":["Orth SR, Ritz E. The Nephrotic Syndrome. New England Journal of Medicine. 1998 Apr 23;338(17):1202\u201311. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/abs/10.1056/NEJM194802122380705","Hunter RW, Welsh N, Farrah TE, Gallacher PJ, Dhaun N. ANCA associated vasculitis. BMJ. 2020;369:m1070. Available at: https://www.bmj.com/content/369/bmj.m1070"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41423"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14101"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41423"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T12:50:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T12:50:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6771"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55875"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":